      "content": "You are absolutely right to be cautious; running Valgrind on a real-time automotive controller is like trying to fit a giant, slow-moving elephant into a tiny, high-speed race car engine—it will kill your timing and violate your hard real-time constraints. The best approach is to use lightweight, targeted instrumentation that adds minimal overhead while still giving you the precision you need to find the culprit.\n\nHere is how you can trace that specific allocation back to its source without tanking performance:\n\n1.  **Use a Lightweight Custom Allocator with Tracing**: Instead of wrapping every single `new` and `delete` globally (which adds significant overhead), create a custom allocator class that only wraps allocations for specific, high-risk objects or data structures you suspect are leaking. You can use a macro like `#define TRACK_ALLOC(ptr)` that only triggers inside those specific functions or classes. This way, you are only adding the \"heavy lifting\" of tracking to the code paths that matter, keeping the rest of the control loop lightning-fast.\n2.  **Implement a \"Stack Trace\" on Allocation**: When your custom allocator detects a `new` operation, instead of just storing the address, store a lightweight pointer to the source file and line number",
